  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Prompt**\n\nI\'m currently breaking down this complex prompt. I\'m focusing on identifying the core user request: a landing page for \"Entre Parrilleros\" to facilitate service requests. I\'m noting the business\'s details (meat and groceries) and the database connection information. Now trying to understand the full user\'s intentions with the database information, Laragon, and the database name.\n\n\n**Defining the Requirements**\n\nI\'ve identified the key features: CRUD operations, form submissions to the database, Google Sheets integration, automated email notifications, monthly sales reports, and an administrative panel for detailed statistics. I\'m focusing on the technical procedures for dashboard updates, considering direct database modifications in Laragon and real-time metric integration using f-strings and dynamic vector graphics. I\'m also preparing to use Plotly Express for an interactive scatter plot.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Analysis**\n\nI\'m now implementing the data analysis, starting with parallel training of Decision Tree and KNN classifiers. I\'ll instantiate both models, setting the Decision Tree\'s max depth to 4 and KNN\'s neighbors to 5. Next, I plan to train them and calculate their accuracy scores using the test data. I also intend to use Pandas for advanced data filtering and aggregation.\n\n\n**Addressing the Local Connection**\n\nI\'ve hit a critical snag. It\'s clear that the application, running in a cloud environment, can\'t directly access the user\'s local Laragon MySQL database. The `localhost` connection is a dead end. I\'m now exploring solutions. Either we\'ll need to develop a server-side backend with local connection capabilities, or we can mock it with an SQLite or data simulator to satisfy the user\'s needs. The immediate focus is on ensuring seamless database handling, given this crucial constraint.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Connection**\n\nI\'ve realized the need for a precise technical guide. My plan involves establishing a database within our cloud application that mirrors the user\'s MySQL table structure. I\'m now crafting instructions explaining how to run our React+Express server locally on their Laragon machine. This will use environment variables (like `DB_HOST`, `DB_USER`, `DB_PASSWORD`, `DB_NAME`, `DB_PORT`) to connect to their live database. We\'ll specify that on their local machine, they should set `DB_HOST=127.0.0.1` and ensure the server can fall back gracefully to a local SQLite or a process in the cloud deployment.\n\n\n**Establishing Database Connections**\n\nI\'m now focusing on ensuring robust database connectivity. I\'ll implement MySQL/MariaDB connection code using the `mysql2` library in the Express backend, configured by environment variables. I\'m adding a fallback mechanism: an in-memory or embedded database if the MySQL connection fails. A warning banner in the admin dashboard will indicate the fallback. My current variables are `MYSQL_HOST`, `MYSQL_USER`, `MYSQL_PASSWORD`, `MYSQL_DATABASE`, and `MYSQL_PORT`. I\'m going to determine Google Sheets integration details.\n\n\n**Integrating Google Sheets**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating Google Sheets and automated email notifications for new orders. I\'ve realized the `workspace-integration` skill with Google Sheets OAuth is ideal. I\'m requesting the `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets` scope via `set_up_oauth`. I\'m verifying available system skills; the `workspace-integration` skill is present and fits the needs. I\'m going to determine a good way to trigger the email notifications.\n\n\n**Evaluating Prediction Services**\n\nI\'m now evaluating various prediction services. Given the user\'s focus on Decision Trees and KNN models, `gemini-api` seems directly relevant. I\'m considering Python scripts, backend services, or even simple TypeScript classifiers. I\'m noting the integration requirements, including Pandas DataFrames and Plotly Express for visualizations. I now realize the best approach will be a server-side prediction service to handle the user\'s detailed instructions for the models.\n\n\n**Adapting Frameworks**\n\nI\'m now grappling with the discrepancy between the requested Python-centric data analysis and our TypeScript/React web application framework. I\'m evaluating the best integration strategy: should I use a backend Python script to handle the Pandas data, scikit-learn models, and Plotly visualizations, or should I implement these directly in TypeScript? I\'m now exploring how to bridge this gap, ensuring that the final application can display results seamlessly.\n\n\n**Evaluating Node.js Implementation**\n\nI\'m now determining if implementing the backend processing inside Node.js is feasible. Given the restrictions on `shell_exec` within the Cloud Run environment, I\'m verifying the potential for Node.js modules to handle data analysis and model execution. This seems to be the only path forward. I\'m focusing on finding the appropriate libraries to replace Python\'s Pandas, scikit-learn, and Plotly functionalities.\n\n\n**Designing the Architecture**\n\nI\'m now devising the system architecture. My aim is to deliver a dynamic dashboard that seamlessly integrates data from the user\'s Laragon MySQL database, Google Sheets, and prediction models. I will create a Node.js Express backend to facilitate real-time updates without page reloads. I\'m focusing on API endpoints for predictions and dashboard data, and will need a Python script to provide visualizations for their Laragon MySQL database, and they want the procedure!\n\n\n**Refining System Integration**\n\nI\'m now refining the system integration, especially Google Sheets and email notifications. My priority is to create an `/api/orders` route that seamlessly inserts order data into the MySQL database. I\'m also preparing to append the order to a Google Sheet using the Google Sheets API and send an automated email notification, either through Nodemailer or a similar service. I\'m exploring robust error handling to gracefully manage optional Google Sheets integration and automated email configurations, potentially using Gemini to create marketing summaries.\n\n\n**Finalizing Technical Documentation**\n\nI\'m now putting the finishing touches on the technical documentation, specifically the real-time data update process. I\'m crafting clear, step-by-step instructions for the Laragon user to modify data directly, and how the dashboard seamlessly reflects those changes. I\'ll include examples of f-string-like multiline string simulations to demonstrate the dynamic display of metrics, ensuring the explanation is both accessible and technically sound. I\'m focusing on making the connection process easy and the technical parts easy to follow.\n\n\n**Visualizing with Plots**\n\nI\'m now implementing interactive visualizations. I can render an engaging scatter plot in the React dashboard, showcasing monthly expenses versus visits, differentiated by churn status, allowing users to filter by branch. Recharts offers a straightforward solution, and I\'m assessing the feasibility of implementing model training or mock predictions directly in TypeScript to enhance the user experience further. I\'m focusing on providing direct code examples for running Python scripts locally.\n\n\n**Examining Package Dependencies**\n\nI\'m now examining the `package.json` file to identify existing npm packages and determine any installation needs. The `mysql2` package appears crucial for database connectivity, and I\'m also considering `nodemailer` or other similar tools for handling email notifications. I\'m focusing on \"lazy initialization and graceful fallback\" for the database connection, specifically supporting multiple SQL engines (MySQL, SQLite fallback) or a clean mock database if the MySQL connection fails. I\'ll implement these, especially focusing on local environments.\n\n\n"
