  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing User Requirements**\n\nI\'m currently dissecting the user\'s request. It seems they need a landing page for a small business (\"Entre Parrilleros\") selling meat and groceries. The user is asking for the ability to perform CRUD operations on a database, specifically to store the customer-filled form data. I\'m focusing on those specific requirements now.\n\n\n**Defining Product Offerings**\n\nI\'ve shifted focus to defining the product offerings for \"Entre Parrilleros.\" It\'s becoming clearer: customers configure custom orders from meat cuts and groceries, or select pre-configured services like \"Parrillada Premium.\" They then complete a detailed order form with personal and branch information. To enable full database CRUD, I\'m proposing a customer-facing order creation screen and an admin panel for viewing, editing, deleting, and manually creating orders.\n\n\n**Integrating Google Sheets**\n\nI\'m now integrating Google Sheets functionality. The goal is to append order data and send automated email notifications. For Google Sheets, I\'m considering a backend integration that appends orders and will offer a detailed explanation, including a mock implementation. Standard integrations will be a primary focus, possibly using environment variables or webhooks, with full documentation. For email notifications, I\'ll explore suitable options next.\n\n\n**Implementing Email Notifications**\n\nI\'m now implementing email notifications using Nodemailer. I\'ll create a `sendEmailNotification` function in `server/email.ts` (or `server.ts`). This will send styled HTML emails to owners and clients. Error handling is crucial; I\'ll log a clear message and show a UI alert if SMTP credentials are missing, ensuring compliance.\nI\'m also working on report generation. The admin panel will feature a \"Download Monthly Report\" button (PDF/Excel/CSV) with a live preview. I\'ll use dynamic CSV or print layouts, incorporating the Gemini API for professional sales summaries.\nI am considering adding an admin panel to visualize detailed order statistics.\n\n\n**Developing the Admin Dashboard**\n\nI\'m now fully focused on the admin dashboard\'s development. I\'m prioritizing overall metrics, visualizations using Recharts for sales trends, branch comparisons, and order status charts. I am concentrating on the integration with data science components for updating data added or modified in the database so that the dashboard updates dynamically. I\'m exploring Plotly Express for generating interactive scatter plots to correlate spending amounts and monthly visits dynamically.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Science**\n\nI am now implementing data science with parallel training of Decision Trees and KNN models for classification, calculating accuracy percentages against test subsets. I\'m also now performing advanced data filtering and aggregation using Pandas, restricting sales data to customers from the \'Osorno Centro\' branch and calculating the mean monthly spend and visits based on customer churn. Additionally, I\'m setting up MySQL and extracting the dataset using a query with JOIN to consolidate relevant information into a Pandas DataFrame, configuring Laragon credentials.\n\n\n**Documenting Machine Learning**\n\nI\'m now focusing on documenting the Python integration for the admin panel\'s data science component. I\'m preparing a detailed documentation screen with the exact Python script for MySQL extraction, data filtering, and parallel model training (Decision Tree and KNN). This includes a dynamic chart export using Plotly Express, and an f-string template for dashboard integration. I\'ll provide clear steps on real-time updates when new transactions are added to the database. I\'m also planning to build a \"Live ML Prediction\" button.\n\n\n**Simulating ML Calculations**\n\nI\'m now implementing a \"Live ML Prediction\" button and an `/api/ml-analysis` API route in Express. This will explain the data science steps, simulate execution on the active database dataset for Osorno Centro, train Decision Tree and KNN models, and output results. I\'m also ensuring full-stack architecture compliance, updating `package.json` scripts, and setting up Vite middleware and React dev server configurations.\n\n\n**Refining Server Configuration**\n\nI\'m now refining the server configuration, ensuring the \"dev,\" \"build,\" and \"start\" scripts in `package.json` are accurate and compliant with the \"type\": \"module\" setting. The use of esbuild to bundle `server.ts` into `dist/server.cjs` and then start it via `node dist/server.cjs` is validated and now in progress. My goal is to ensure this will be modular and robust. I\'m moving on to defining the data storage structure, considering SQLite, in-memory SQL, and file-based JSON fallback options in `/data/parrillero.json`.\n\n\n**Establishing Database Connectivity**\n\nI\'m now establishing database connectivity. I\'ll create a `server/db.ts` file to manage this, attempting a MySQL connection using `mysql2/promise` with `.env` settings. If the connection fails, likely due to a local Laragon instance not being accessible, I\'ll log a fallback message. This implementation will include standard CRUD operations like `getOrders`, `createOrder`, `updateOrder`, and `deleteOrder`. I\'m going to start with a fallback to an in-memory database with pre-populated demo data, or a file-based JSON fallback, depending on the availability of MySQL credentials in the `.env` file.\n\n\n**Defining API Endpoints**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining the API endpoints within `server.ts`. I\'ll set up an Express app to handle CRUD operations for orders, including GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE routes. Additionally, I\'ll create an `/api/ml-analysis` endpoint that computes statistics and simulates classification models to provide insights from the Osorno Centro branch. I will also make sure to serve the project files.\n\n\n**Designing Database Integration**\n\nI\'m now designing the database connection. I will define a safe database wrapper in `server/db.ts` to prevent crashes if MySQL isn\'t available. The wrapper will use a connection pool with `mysql2/promise` and `.env` settings for Laragon, with a fallback to in-memory storage or a JSON file if the connection fails. This fallback will also be used to store pre-populated demo data, including simulating APIs. I am also working on creating Google Sheets and email APIs. I need to handle Vite middleware as well.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Simulation**\n\nI\'m now implementing data simulation. I\'m focusing on crafting a comprehensive dataset with mock sales data, including customer details, order items, and branch information to ensure a functional system. I will test diverse scenarios, including variable customer spending, frequency, and order status, ensuring the accuracy and effectiveness of the simulated output data. I will include a detailed `created_at` timestamp.\n\n\n**Refining Data Simulation**\n\nI\'m now refining data simulation with focus on incorporating customer churn flags and ensuring data variety. I\'m building data variations, setting realistic spending habits, visit frequencies, and order statuses, including a detailed `created_at` timestamp. I will also incorporate churn flags based on spending and activity for Osorno Centro branch.\n\n\n**Simulating Diverse Scenarios**\n\nI\'m now implementing the diverse sales data scenarios. I\'ve enriched the mock dataset with \"fuga\" (churn) flags based on spending and activity for Osorno Centro. I\'m focusing on ensuring data variations for realistic spending habits, visit frequencies, and order statuses, including a detailed `created_at` timestamp. I\'m aiming for comprehensive functional system data.\n\n\n\n**Calculating ML Accuracies**\n\nI\'m now calculating ML accuracies using simulated data. I can now write server-side functions to compute and display the ML model accuracies, means, and other relevant metrics. The dataset includes Osorno Centro branch customers, churn flags, spending, and visits, allowing accurate calculations and visualizations.\n\n\n**Validating Algorithm Feasibility**\n\nI\'m now validating the feasibility of a mini training algorithm in TypeScript. I\'ve confirmed that a simplified Decision Tree (depth=4) and KNN (n_neighbors=5) can be implemented directly in TS. I\'ll use Euclidean distance for KNN and threshold splits for the Decision Tree, applying this to a simulated dataset with monthly spending, visits, and a churn flag (`is_fuga`). I\'ll use a mini 8-element dataset to verify the rules and calculations and then seed a larger one to make the results more credible.\n\n\n"
